/* Sir Gawain and the Green Knight.
   English is an original translation. The Middle English shown alongside is
   lightly normalised from Richard Morris's 1864 edition (Cotton Nero A.x,
   Project Gutenberg #14568, public domain): thorn (þ) -> th, yogh (3) -> y/gh,
   ampersand -> and, folio markers and editor's sidenote letters removed; bob-
   and-wheel run into the prose. The full diplomatic source is preserved at
   source/sggk-morris-1864.txt. Attaches to window.GAWAIN. */
window.GAWAIN = window.GAWAIN || {};
window.GAWAIN.tale = {
  meta: {
    blurb: "<strong>Sir Gawain and the Green Knight</strong> — the masterpiece of late-14th-century Middle English alliterative verse, anonymous (the <em>Pearl Poet</em>), surviving in one manuscript (BL Cotton Nero A.x). Below are <strong>Fitts I &amp; II</strong> in full (45 stanzas, ~1,125 lines): the Trojan frame, Christmas at Camelot, the Green Knight's entrance and the beheading game; then the turn of the seasons, the arming of Gawain with the pentangle, the wilderness ride, the arrival at Bertilak's castle and the exchange-of-winnings bargain. The English is an <strong>original translation</strong>. The Middle English beside it is a <em>lightly normalised reading text</em> after Richard Morris's 1864 edition (Project Gutenberg #14568, public domain) — thorns and yoghs modernised for readability; the diplomatic source is preserved verbatim at <a href=\"source/sggk-morris-1864.txt\">source/sggk-morris-1864.txt</a>.",
    sources: [
      { label: "Sir Gawayne and the Green Knight — Richard Morris (1864), Project Gutenberg #14568", url: "https://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/14568", host: "Project Gutenberg" },
      { label: "Cotton Nero A.x — BL digitised manuscript", url: "https://www.bl.uk/manuscripts/Viewer.aspx?ref=cotton_ms_nero_a_x", host: "British Library" },
      { label: "Sir Gawain and the Green Knight — background", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Gawain_and_the_Green_Knight", host: "Wikipedia" },
    ],
  },
  roadmap: [
    { t: "Source text in hand", done: true },
    { t: "Fitt I · The beheading at Camelot", done: true },
    { t: "Fitt II · Gawain rides out, Bertilak's castle", done: true },
    { t: "Fitt III · Three hunts, three temptations, the green girdle", done: false },
    { t: "Fitt IV · The Green Chapel and what was revealed", done: false },
  ],
  passages: [
    {
      title: "Fitt I. The Green Knight at Camelot",
      segments: [
        { w: "Sithen the sege and the assaut was sesed at Troye, the borgh brittened and brent to brondes and askes, the tulk that the trammes of tresoun ther wroght was tried for his tricherie, the trewest on erthe. Hit was Ennias the athel, and his highe kynde, that sithen depreced provinces, and patrounes bicome welneghe of al the wele in the west iles. Fro riche Romulus to Rome ricchis hym swythe, with gret bobbaunce that burghe he biges upon fyrst, and neuenes hit his aune nome, as hit now hat; Ticius to Tuskan turnes, and teldes bigynnes; Langaberde in Lumbardie lyftes up homes; and fer over the French flod Felix Brutus on mony bonkkes ful brode Bretayn he settes, wyth wynne. Where werre, and wrake, and wonder, by sythes hath wont ther-inne, and oft bothe blysse and blunder ful skete hath skyfted synne.",
          e: "When the siege and assault of Troy were ended — the city beaten down to brands and ashes, and the man who had spun the looms of treason there tried for his treachery, the truest traitor on earth — it was noble Aeneas and his high kindred who afterwards subdued provinces and became the lords of almost all the wealth of the western isles. From him came rich Romulus, who hurried to Rome, and with great proud display first raised that city and named it with his own name, as it bears now; Ticius turned to Tuscany and began to build there; Langobard set up homes in Lombardy; and far over the French sea, upon many broad hillsides, Felix Brutus founded Britain with delight — Britain, where war, and ruin, and wonder have many a time held sway, and where bliss and blunder by turns have very swiftly shifted since.",
          n: "The opening trick of the high alliterative tradition: tie Britain's origin back to Troy through the legendary founder Brutus, with Geoffrey of Monmouth's pseudo-history serving the New Year tale." },

        { w: "And quen this Bretayn was bigged by this burn rych, bolde bredden ther-inne, baret that lofden, in mony turned tyme tene that wroghten. Mo ferlyes on this folde han fallen here oft then in any other that I wot, syn that ilk tyme. Bot of alle that here bult of Bretaygne kynges ay was Arthur the hendest, as I haf herde telle; for-thi an aunter in erde I attle to schawe, that a selly in sight summe men hit holden, and an outtrage aventure of Arthures wonderes. If ye wyl lysten this laye but on littel quile, I schal telle hit, as-tit, as I in toun herde, with tonge; as hit is stad and stoken, in stori stif and stronge, with lel letteres loken, in londe so hath ben longe.",
          e: "And after this Britain had been raised by that noble lord, bold men flourished here, men that loved battle, and in many a turning time they wrought trouble. More marvels have fallen on this land since that same time than in any other I know of. But of all who ever ruled in Britain, Arthur was ever the noblest, as I have heard told — and so I mean to set out an adventure on earth, a sight some hold for a marvel beyond marvels, an outrage-adventure of Arthur's wonders. If you will listen to my lay only a little while, I shall tell it now, as I heard it told in town, by tongue — as it stands and is fastened in a story strong and stiff, locked in with loyal letters, as it has long been kept in this land." },

        { w: "This kyng lay at Camylot upon Krystmasse, with mony luflych lorde, ledes of the best, rekenly of the rounde table alle tho rich brether, with rych revel oryght, and rechles merthes; ther tournayed tulkes by-tymes ful mony, justed ful jolilé thise gentyle knyghtes, sythen kayred to the court, caroles to make. For ther the fest was ilyche ful fiften dayes, with alle the mete and the mirthe that men couthe a-vyse; such glaumande gle glorious to here, dere dyn upon day, daunsyng on nyghtes, al was hap upon heghe in halles and chambres, with lordes and ladies, as leuest him thoght; with all the wele of the worlde thay woned ther samen, the most kyd knyghtes under Kryste seluen, and the louelokkest ladies that euer lif haden, and he the comlokest kyng that the court haldes; for al was this fayre folk in her first age, on sille; the hapnest under heuen, kyng hyghest mon of wylle, hit were now gret nye to neuen so hardy a here on hille.",
          e: "This king lay at Camelot at Christmas, with many lovely lords, the choicest of men — gathered in good order, the whole rich brotherhood of the Round Table — in rich revelry indeed, with reckless mirth. Knights tilted at tournament many times; the gentle knights jousted gaily, then turned back to court to make carols. There the feast ran on, full for fifteen days, with all the meat and the mirth that men could devise. Such cheerful glee was glorious to hear — a fine din through the day, dancing through the night, all happiness on high in halls and chambers among lords and ladies as they best loved. With all the world's wealth they dwelt there together — the most renowned knights under Christ Himself, the loveliest ladies that ever lived, and he the comeliest king that holds a court — for all this fair folk in the hall were in their first youth, the happiest under heaven, and the king the man of highest will. It would now be hard to name so bold a band on any hill." },

        { w: "Wyle nw yer was so yep that hit was nwe cummen, that day double on the dece was the douth serued, fro the kyng was cummen with knyghtes in-to the halle, the chauntre of the chapel cheued to an ende; loude crye was ther kest of clerkes and other, Nowel nayted o-newe, neuened ful ofte; and sythen riche forth runnen to reche honde-selle, yeghed yeres yiftes on hi, yelde hem by hond, debated busyly aboute tho giftes; ladies laghed ful loude, thoghe thay lost haden, and he that wan was not wrothe, that may ye wel trawe. Alle this mirthe thay maden to the mete tyme; when thay had waschen, worthyly thay wenten to sete, the best burne ay abof, as hit best semed; whene Guenore ful gay, graythed in the myddes, dressed on the dere des, dubbed al aboute, smal sendal bisides, a selure hir ouer of tryed Tolouse, of Tars tapites in-noghe, that were enbrawded and beten wyth the best gemmes, that myght be preued of prys wyth penyes to bye, in daye; the comlokest to discrye, ther glent with yghen gray, a semloker that euer he syghe, soth moght no mon say.",
          e: "While the New Year was still so young, just newly come, the company was that day doubly served upon the dais. Once the king had come with his knights into the hall, the chanting in the chapel ended; loud cries were cast up by clerics and others — “Nowell!” renewed and named often. And then the company hurried forth to receive their handsels, calling out New Year's gifts on high and handing them out, busily debating the giving. Ladies laughed aloud, though they had lost, and he that had won was not wrathful — you may well believe it. All this mirth they made until the time for meat; when they had washed, worthily they went to their seats — the best man always above, as best became him; bright Guinevere, gaily attired, was set in the midst, placed upon the rich dais and decked all about with smooth sendal silk beside her and a canopy above of fine Toulouse silk and abundant tapestries of Tarsia, embroidered and beaten with the best of gems — gems whose worth no day's wages could prove. Yet she herself, the comeliest to behold, who glanced about with grey eyes — a fairer lady than he had ever set eyes on, in truth no man could claim." },

        { w: "Bot Arthure wolde not ete til al were serued, he was so joly of his joyfnes, and sum-quat child gered, his lif liked hym lyght, he louied the lasse auther to lenge lye, or to longe sitte, so by-sied him his yonge blod and his brayn wylde; and also another maner meued him eke, that he thurgh nobelay had nomen, ho wolde neuer ete upon such a dere day, er hym deuised were of sum auenturus thyng an uncouthe tale, of sum mayn meruayle, that he myght trawe, of alderes, of armes, of other auenturus, other sum segg hym bi-soght of sum siker knyght, to joyne wyth hym in justyng in jopardé to lay, lede lif for lyf, leue uchon other, as fortune wolde fulsun hom the fayrer to haue. This was the kynges countenaunce where he in court were, at uch farand fest among his fre meny, in halle; therfore of face so fere, he stightles stif in stalle, ful yep in that nw yere, much mirthe he mas with alle.",
          e: "But Arthur would not eat until all were served. He was so glad in his youth and a little childlike — his life pleased him light, and he liked the less either to lie long abed or sit long at table, for his young blood and wild brain so urged him. And besides, another custom moved him, taken on himself for honour's sake: he would never eat upon such a high day until he had been told some adventurous thing, some uncouth tale of a great marvel he could believe — of patriarchs, of arms, of other adventures — or some man had asked him for a sure knight to join with him in a joust, to set life against life, each yielding place to the other, and let fortune help whichever should be the fairer. This was the king's custom whenever he was at court, at every grand feast among his free company in hall; and so, with that bold face of his, he stands stiff in his seat, fully youthful in that new year, and makes much mirth with all.",
          n: "The custom — \"no meat till a marvel\" — is the door the Green Knight will walk through. The poem's irony is that the marvel Arthur gets is darker than any he expected." },

        { w: "Thus ther stondes in stale the stif kyng his-seluen, talkkande bifore the hyghe table of trifles ful hende. Ther gode Gawan was graythed, Gwenore bisyde, and Agrauayn a la dure mayn on that other syde sittes, bothe the kynges sister sunes, and ful siker knyghtes; bischop Bawdewyn abof bi-gines the table, and Ywan, Vryn son, ette wit hym-seluen; thise were dight on the des, and derworthly serued, and sythen mony siker segge at the sidbordes. Then the first cors come with crakkyng of trumpes, wyth mony baner ful bryght, that ther-by henged, nwe nakryn noyse with the noble pipes, wylde werbles and wyght wakned lote, that mony hert ful hy hef at her towches; dayntes dryuen ther-wyth of ful dere metes, foysoun of the fresche, and on so fele disches, that pine to fynde the place the peple bi-forne for to sette the syluener, that sere sewes halden, on clothe; iche lede as he loued hym-selue ther laght with-outen lothe, ay two had disches twelue, good ber, and bryght wyn bothe.",
          e: "Thus stands the stalwart king in his place, talking before the high table of trifles in courtly fashion. Beside Queen Guinevere sat good Gawain, and on her other hand Agravain of the Hard Hand — both of them the king's sister's sons and very sure knights. Above them began the table Bishop Baldwin, and Ywain the son of Urien ate with him. These were seated on the dais and royally served, and many trusty knights at the side-tables after. Then the first course came in with cracking of trumpets, with many a bright banner hung beside them, with new nakers' noise and the noble pipes, with wild warblings and lively rousing notes that lifted many a heart at their music. Then the daintiest of the dearest meats were brought, abundance of fresh game and so many dishes that it was hard to find room before the people to set down the silver platters bearing the courses, upon the cloth; each man took his share without grudging, as he best liked — every two had twelve dishes between them, with good beer and bright wine, both." },

        { w: "Now wyl I of hor seruise say yow no more, for uch wyghe may wel wit no wont that ther were; an other noyse ful newe neghed biliue, that the lude myght haf leue lif-lode to cach. For unethe was the noyce not a whyle sesed, and the fyrst cource in the court kyndely serued, ther hales in at the halle dor an aghlich mayster, on the most on the molde on mesure hyghe; fro the swyre to the swange so sware and so thik, and his lyndes and his lymes so longe and so grete, half etayn in erde I hope that he were. Bot mon most I algate mynn hym to bene, and that the myriest in his muckel that myght ride; for of bak and of brest al were his bodi sturne, bot his wombe and his wast were worthily smale, and alle his fetures folghande, in forme that he hade, ful clene; for wonder of his hwe men hade, set in his semblaunt sene; he ferde as freke were fade, and ouer-al enker grene.",
          e: "I will say no more of their serving, for every man may well know there was no lack of anything there. Then another sound, quite new, drew near; the company might leave off taking their food. For scarcely had the music ceased a moment, and the first course been properly served, when there came striding in at the hall door an awesome lord — the tallest of all men on the earth in measure. From the neck to the waist he was so square and so thick, and his loins and his limbs so long and so great, that I believe he must have been half a giant. Yet I will hold him to be a man all the same — and the merriest of his great size that ever bestrode a horse. For though his back and his breast were thick and stern, his belly and his waist were properly small, and all his features matched his frame fittingly. Folk wondered at his hue, plain to see in his very look: he moved like a man fierce and free — and all over he was vividly green.",
          n: "The Pearl Poet's most famous tableau. The Green Knight is one of the great visual inventions in all medieval literature — the colour itself is the wonder." },

        { w: "And al graythed in grene this gome and his wedes, a strayt cote ful streght, that stek on his sides, a mere mantile abof, mensked with-inne, with pelure pured apert the pane ful clene, with blythe blaunner ful bryght, and his hod bothe, that was laght fro his lokkes, and layde on his schulderes; heme wel haled, hose of that same grene, that spenet on his sparlyr, and clene spures vnder, of bryght golde, vpon silk bordes, barred ful ryche; and scholes vnder schankes, there the schalk rides; and alle his vesture verayly was clene verdure, bothe the barres of his belt and other blythe stones, that were richely rayled in his aray clene, aboutte hym-self and his sadel, vpon silk werkes, that were to tor for to telle of tryfles the halue, that were enbrauded abof, wyth bryddes and flyes, with gay gaudi of grene, the golde ay in myddes; the pendauntes of his payttrure, the proude cropure, his molaynes, and alle the metail anamayld was thenne, the steropes that he stod on, stayned of the same, and his arsouns al after, and his athel sturtes, that euer glemered and glent al of grene stones. The fole that he ferkkes on, fyn of that ilke, sertayn; a grene hors gret and thikke, a stede ful stif to strayne, in brawden brydel quik, to the gome he was ful gayn.",
          e: "And this man and his garments were all decked in green: a close-fitting tunic that clung tight to his sides, with a fair mantle above it richly trimmed within with clean white ermine — and his hood likewise, thrown back from his locks and laid over his shoulders. Well-fitted hose of the same green clung to his calves, and bright spurs beneath, of gleaming gold, set upon silken straps cunningly barred; the rider went shoeless. All his vesture was the cleanest green: the bars of his belt, the bright stones richly arranged in his array, the saddle and the saddle-cloth — silken work too elaborate to tell more than half its trifles, embroidered above with birds and flies, with gay green ornament and gold always at the centre. The pendants of his breast-band, the proud crupper-strap, the bosses of his bit, and all the metal-work were enamelled; the stirrups he stood in were stained the same, and the saddle-bows after, and the noble harness-skirts, all gleaming and glittering with green stones. The horse he rode upon was perfectly matched with him: a great thick green horse, a steed stiff to govern, prompt in the plaited bridle — and altogether well-suited to his rider." },

        { w: "Wel gay was this gome gered in grene, and the here of his hed of his hors swete; fayre fannand fax umbe-foldes his schulderes; a much berd as a busk ouer his brest henges, that wyth his hyghlich here, that of his hed reches, was euesed al umbe-torne, a-bof his elbowes, that half his armes ther vnder were halched in the wyse of a kynges capados, that closes his swyre. The mane of that mayn hors much to hit lyke, wel cresped and cemmed wyth knottes ful mony, folden in wyth fildore aboute the fayre grene, ay a herle of the here, an other of golde; the tayl and his toppyng twynnen of a sute, and bounden bothe wyth a bande of a bryght grene, dubbed wyth ful dere stones, as the dok lasted; sythen thrawen wyth a thwong a thwarle knot alofte, ther mony belles ful bryght of brende golde rungen. Such a fole upon folde, ne freke that hym rydes, was neuer sene in that sale wyth syght er that tyme, with yghe; he loked as layt so lyght, so sayd al that hym syghe, hit semed as no mon myght, vnder his dyntes dryghe.",
          e: "Gaily was this man arrayed in green, and the hair of his head matched his horse's. A fair fanning fall of locks folded over his shoulders, and a beard as great as a bush hung down upon his breast — beard and high head-hair together trimmed evenly all around above his elbows, so that half his arms below were enclosed under them, in the fashion of a king's cape that wraps his neck. The mane of his mighty horse was much the same: well-curled and combed and knotted in many places, plaited through with gold thread along the fair green — a strand of hair to a strand of gold. Tail and forelock were twinned in the same way, and both bound with a bright green band, set with full-rich stones along its length, knotted up with a thong in a tight knot at the top, from which many bright bells of refined gold rang. Such a horse on the earth, and such a knight to ride him, was never seen in that hall with mortal eye, not before that time — he looked as bright as a stroke of lightning, said all who saw him: it seemed that no man might endure his blow." },

        { w: "Whether hade he no helme ne hawbergh nauther, ne no pysan, ne no plate that pented to armes, ne no schafte, ne no schelde, to schwne ne to smyte, bot in his on honde he hade a holyn bobbe, that is grattest in grene, when greues ar bare, and an ax in his other, a hoge and vn-mete, a spetos sparthe to expoun in spelle quo-so myght. The hede of an eln-yerde the large lenkthe hade, the grayn al of grene stele and of golde hewen, the bit burnyst bryght, with a brod egge, as wel schapen to schere as scharp rasores; the stele of a stif staf the sturne hit bi-grypte, that was wounden wyth yrn to the wandes ende, and al bigrauen with grene, in gracios werkes; a lace lapped aboute, that louked at the hede, and so after the halme halched ful ofte, wyth tryed tassels therto tacched in-noghe, on botouns of the bryght grene brayden ful ryche. This hathel heldes hym in, and the halle entres, driuande to the heghe dece, dut he no wothe, haylsed he neuer one, but heghe he ouer loked. The fyrst word that he warp, “wher is,” he sayd, “the gouernour of this gyng? Gladly I wolde se that segg in syght, and with hym self speke raysoun.” To knyghtes he kest his yghe, and reled hym up and doun, he stemmed and con studie, quo walt ther most renoun.",
          e: "He had no helm and no hauberk either, no plate-armour that belongs to arms, no spear and no shield to ward or to strike with — but in one hand he held a holly bough, the greenest thing in the wood when the thickets are bare, and in the other an axe, huge and out of measure, a fearsome battleaxe to expound in words for any that could. The head of it was an ell long, broad as a yard, the steel green and chased with gold, the blade burnished bright with a broad edge, as well shaped for shearing as the sharpest razor. The haft was a stiff staff that the stern man gripped, wound with iron to the end of the handle and all engraved in green with graceful work; a lace was lapped about it, fastening at the head and so wound often along the haft, with rich tassels tied to it on buttons of bright green, abundantly embroidered. This lord rode his horse straight into the hall, drove up to the high dais without fear of any harm, never greeted anyone, but looked high over them all. The first word he uttered: “Where is,” he said, “the governor of this gathering? Gladly would I see that man in the eye and speak with him in reason.” He cast his eye over the knights and rolled it up and down, paused, and pondered who held the most renown there.",
          n: "Holly in one hand (peace) and a great axe in the other (war) — the Green Knight's costume is itself the puzzle." },

        { w: "Ther was lokyng on lenthe, the lude to be-holde, for uch mon had meruayle quat hit mene myght, that a hathel and a horse myght such a hwe lach, as growe grene as the gres and grener hit semed, then grene aumayl on golde lowande bryghter. Al studied that ther stod, and stalked hym nerre, wyth al the wonder of the worlde, what he worch schulde. For fele sellyes had thay sen, but such neuer are, for-thi for fantoum and fayryghe the folk there hit demed; therfore to answare was arghe mony athel freke, and al stouned at his steuen, and stonstil seten, in a swoghe sylence thurgh the sale riche, as al were slypped vpon slepe so slaked hor lotes in hyghe; I deme hit not al for doute, but sum for cortaysye, but let hym that al schulde loute, cast vnto that wyghe.",
          e: "There was looking long to behold this lord; every man marvelled what it might mean that a knight and a horse should take such a hue — to grow as green as the grass, and greener it seemed even than that, brighter than green enamel glowing on gold. All who stood there studied him and stepped nearer in wonder of the world, what he might do. Many marvels they had seen, but never such a one — and so they reckoned him a phantom and a fairy thing. Therefore many a noble warrior was afraid to answer, and all astounded at his voice, sat as still as stones, in a swooning silence through the rich hall, as though all had slipped into sleep, so slack went their voices on the sudden. I do not reckon it all for fear — but some for courtesy — letting him to whom they all owed obedience be the one to address that man.",
          n: "“For phantom and fairy thing they deemed it”: from the first instant Camelot reads the Green Knight as Otherworld — and they are right." },

        { w: "Thenn Arthour bifore the hi dece that auenture byholdes, and rekenly hym reuerenced, for rad was he neuer, and sayde, “wyghe, welcum iwys to this place, the hede of this ostel Arthour I hat, lyght luflych adoun, and lenge, I the praye, and quat so thy wylle is, we schal wyt after.” “Nay, as help me,” quod the hathel, “he that on hyghe syttes, to wone any quyle in this won, hit was not myn ernde; bot for the los of the lede is lyft up so hyghe, and thy burgh and thy burnes best ar holden, stifest vnder stel-gere on stedes to ryde, the wyghtest and the worthyest of the worldes kynde, preue for to play wyth in other pure laykes; and here is kydde cortaysye, as I haf herd carp, and that hath wayned me hider, I-wyis, at this tyme. Ye may be seker by this braunch that I bere here, that I passe as in pes, and no plyght seche; for had I founded in fere, in feghtyng wyse, I haue a hauberghe at home and a helme bothe, a schelde, and a scharp spere, schinande bryght, ande other weppenes to welde, I wene wel als, but for I wolde no were, my wedes ar softer. But if thou be so bold as alle burnes tellen, thou wyl grant me godly the gomen that I ask, by ryght.” Arthour con onsware, and sayd, “sir cortays knyght, if thou craue batayl bare, here failes thou not to fyght.”",
          e: "Then Arthur looked upon the adventure before the high dais, and graciously gave him reverence — for he was never afraid — and said: “Sir, welcome indeed to this place. The head of this house am I, Arthur. Alight, I pray you, gently, and stay; and whatever your will is, we shall learn it after.” “Nay, so help me,” said the lord, “He that sits on high — to dwell any while in this dwelling was not my errand. But because the renown of you here is lifted up so high, and your city and your knights held best — stiffest in armour, riding on steeds, the bravest and the worthiest of the world's kindred, proven to play with in other noble games — and because here is famed courtesy, as I have heard it told, that has summoned me hither in truth at this time. You may be sure by this branch that I bear here that I come in peace and seek no quarrel; for had I set out in arms, in fighting wise, I have a hauberk at home, and a helm too, a shield, and a sharp spear shining bright, and other weapons to wield I know well also — but because I wanted no war, my garments are softer. Yet if you are as bold as all men tell, you will graciously grant me the game that I ask of right.” Arthur answered and said: “Sir courteous knight, if you crave a bare-handed combat, here you shall not fail to find a fight.”" },

        { w: "“Nay, frayst I no fyght, in fayth I the telle, hit arn aboute on this bench but berdles chylder; if I were hasped in armes on a heghe stede, here is no mon me to mach, for myghtes so wayke. For-thy I craue in this court a crystmas gomen, for hit is yol and nwe yer, and here ar yep mony; if any so hardy in this hous holdes hym-seluen, be so bolde in his blod, brayn in hys hede, that dar stifly strike a strok for an other, I schal gif hym of my gyft thys giserne ryche, this ax, that is heué in-nogh, to hondele as hym lykes, and I schal bide the fyrst bur, as bare as I sitte. If any freke be so felle to fonde that I telle, lepe lyghtly me to, and lach this weppen, I quit clayme hit for euer, kepe hit as his auen, and I schal stonde hym a strok, stif on this flet, elles thou wyl dyght me the dom to dele hym an other, barlay; and yet gif hym respite, a twelmonyth and a day; — now hyghe, and let se tite, dar any her-inne oght say.”",
          e: "“Nay, I seek no fight, in faith I tell you — there are but beardless children all about on this bench. Were I clasped in armour on a high steed, here is no man to match me, for the might here is so weak. So I crave in this court a Christmas game; it is Yule and New Year, and here are many lusty men. If any here is so hardy as to hold himself bold of blood and brave-brained in his head, and dares stoutly strike a stroke for another, I shall give him as my gift this rich battleaxe — this axe, heavy enough, to handle as he likes — and I shall abide the first blow as bare as I sit. If any fellow is fierce enough to take up what I propose, let him leap lightly to me and grasp this weapon — I quit-claim it forever, let him keep it as his own — and I shall stand his stroke standing firm on this floor, on one condition: that you grant me the right to deal him another in turn, in fair exchange, and yet give him grace, a twelvemonth and a day. Now then, be quick, and let us see whether any here dares say a word.”",
          n: "The beheading game — a Celtic motif also found in the older Irish tale Bricriu's Feast. The bargain is impossible: any man who takes the blow must know the return is death." },

        { w: "If he hem stowned vpon fyrst, stiller were thanne alle the hered-men in halle, the hyghe and the loghe; the renk on his rounce hym ruched in his sadel, and runisch-ly his rede yghen he reled aboute, bende his bresed broghes, bly-cande grene, wayued his berde for to wayte quo-so wolde ryse. When non wolde kepe hym with carp he coghed ful hyghe, ande rimed hym ful richley, and ryght hym to speke: “What, is this Arthures hous,” quod the hathel thenne, “that al the rous rennes of, thurgh ryalmes so mony? Where is now your sourquydrye and your conquestes, your gryndel-layk, and your greme, and your grete wordes? Now is the reuel and the renoun of the rounde table ouer-walt wyth a worde of on wyghes speche; for al dares for drede, with-oute dynt schewed!” Wyth this he laghes so loude, that the lorde greued; the blod schot for scham in-to his schyre face and lere; he wex as wroth as wynde, so did alle that ther were, the kyng as kene by kynde, then stod that stif mon nere.",
          e: "If he had startled them at first, stiller still then were all the household in hall, both the high and the low. The lord on his rouncey shifted himself in his saddle, and savagely rolled his red eyes about, bent his bristled brows, glittering green; waved his beard, watching to see who would rise. When none would meet him with a word, he coughed loudly, and stretched himself in lordly fashion, and made ready to speak again. “What — is this Arthur's house,” said the lord then, “of which the rumour runs through so many realms? Where now is your proud spirit and your conquests, your fierce-fighting, your wrath, your great words? Now is the revel and the renown of the Round Table overturned by one word of one man's speech — for all of you flinch in fear before any blow is even given!” With that he laughed so loud that the king was grieved; the blood shot for shame into his fair face and his cheek. He grew as wroth as the wind, and so did all that were there; the king, keen by nature, then stood close before that stout man." },

        { w: "And sayde, “hathel, by heuen thyn askyng is nys, and as thou foly hath frayst, fynde the be-houes; I know no gome that is gast of thy grete wordes. Gif me now thy geserne, vpon godes halue, and I schal baythen thy bone, that thou boden habbes.” Lyghtly lepes he hym to, and laght at his honde; then feersly that other freke vpon fote lyghtis. Now hath Arthure his axe, and the halme grypes, and sturnely stures hit aboute, that stryke wyth hit thoght. The stif mon hym bifore stod vpon hyght, herre then ani in the hous by the hede and more; wyth sturne schere ther he stod, he stroked his berde, and wyth a countenaunce dryghe he droghe doun his cote, no more mate ne dismayd for hys mayn dintes, then any burne vpon bench hade broght hym to drynk of wyne. Gawan, that sate by the quene, to the kyng he can enclyne, “I be-seche now with sagghes sene, this melly mot be myne.”",
          e: "And he said: “Sir, by heaven your asking is folly, and as you have sought folly, find it you must. I know no man here afraid of your great words. Give me your axe now, in God's name, and I shall grant the boon that you have asked.” Lightly he leapt to him and laid hold of his hand; then fiercely that other man stepped down on foot. Now Arthur has the axe, and grips the haft, and stoutly swings it about, as one who means to strike with it. The bold knight stood before him on his feet, taller than any in the hall by a head and more; with stern face there he stood, stroking his beard, and with a dry countenance drew down his coat — no more dismayed at the coming great blow than if any man at the bench had brought him a drink of wine. Then Gawain, who sat beside the queen, bowed to the king: “I beseech you now in plain words, let this fight be mine.”" },

        { w: "“Wolde ye, worthylych lorde,” quod Gawan to the kyng, “bid me boghe fro this benche, and stonde by yow there, that I wyth-oute vylanye myght voyde this table, and that my legge lady lyked not ille, I wolde com to your counseyl, bifore your cort ryche. For me think hit not semly, as hit is soth knawen, ther such an askyng is heuened so hyghe in your sale, thaghe ye yourself be talenttyf to take hit to your-seluen, whil mony so bolde yow aboute vpon bench sytten, that vnder heuen, I hope, non haghe er of wylle, ne better bodyes on bent, ther baret is rered. I am the wakkest, I wot, and of wyt feblest, and lest lur of my lyf, quo laytes the sothe, but for as much as ye ar myn em, I am only to prayse, no bounté but your blod I in my bodé knowe; and sythen this note is so nys, that noght hit yow falles, and I haue frayned hit at yow fyrst, foldes hit to me, and if I carp not comlyly, let alle this cort rych, bout blame.” Ryche to-geder con roun, and sythen thay redden alle same, to ryd the kyng wyth croun, and gif Gawan the game.",
          e: "“Would you, honoured lord,” said Gawain to the king, “bid me rise from this bench and stand by you there — that I might without discourtesy leave this table, and so my liege lady be not displeased — I would come to your counsel before this rich court. For it seems to me not seemly, as is widely known to be the truth, that when such an asking is raised so high in your hall, you yourself, though willing to take it on yourself, should answer it, while so many bold men sit about you on your benches — than whom, I believe, none under heaven is keener of will, no better bodies on a battlefield where strife is raised. I am the weakest of them, I know, and feeblest of wit, and the loss of my life would be the least of any, whoever looks at the truth; only that you are my uncle is any praise to me — no virtue beyond your blood do I know in my body. And since this is so foolish a matter that it is in no way for you, and since I have first asked it of you, hand it over to me; and if I do not speak fittingly, let this rich court blame me, with no blame to you.” The nobles whispered together — and then they all agreed, to free the crowned king and give Gawain the game.",
          n: "Gawain's intervention is one of the most famous courtly speeches in Middle English — exquisite humility that is also a quietly perfect manoeuvre, since it shames no one and gives Arthur a graceful way out." },

        { w: "Then comaunded the kyng the knyght for to ryse; and he ful radly vp ros, and ruchched hym fayre, kneled doun bifore the kyng, and cacches that weppen; and he luflyly hit hym laft, and lyfte vp his honde, and gef hym goddes blessyng, and gladly hym biddes that his hert and his honde schulde hardi be bothe. “Kepe the cosyn,” quod the kyng, “that thou on kyrf sette, and if thou redes hym ryght, redly I trowe, that thou schal byden the bur that he schal bede after.” Gawan gots to the gome, with giserne in honde, and he baldly hym bydes, he bayst neuer the helder, then carppes to sir Gawan the knyght in the grene, “Refourme we oure for-wardes, er we fyrre passe. Fyrst I ethe the, hathel, how that thou hattes, that thou me telle truly, as I tryst may?” “In god fayth,” quod the goode knyght, “Gawan I hatte, that bede the this buffet, quat-so bi-falles after, and at this tyme twelmonyth take at the another, wyth what weppen so thou wylt, and wyth no wyghe elles, on lyue.” That other on-swares agayn, “Sir Gawan, so mot I thryue, as I am ferly fayn, this dint that thou schal dryue.”",
          e: "Then the king commanded the knight to rise; and he rose up promptly and made himself ready, knelt down before the king, and took up the weapon. The king kindly let it pass to him, and lifted his hand, and gave him God's blessing, and gladly bade him be both hardy of heart and of hand. “Take care, cousin,” said the king, “that you set your cut aright; and if you handle him as you should, I truly believe you shall be able to abide the blow he shall give back after.” Gawain steps up to the knight, axe in hand, and the other boldly awaits him, never abashed in the slightest. Then the knight in the green spoke to Sir Gawain: “Let us go over our bargain again before we go further. First I ask you, sir, what is your name — that you tell me truly, that I may trust it?” “In good faith,” said the good knight, “Gawain I am called — I who give you this buffet, whatever may befall after; and at this time a twelvemonth from now, I shall take from you another, with whatever weapon you choose, and from no other man living.” The other answers him again: “Sir Gawain, as I may thrive, I am most glad that you shall deal this blow.”" },

        { w: "“By God,” quod the grene knyght, “sir Gawan, melykes, that I schal fange at thy fust that I haf frayst here; and thou hath redily rehersed, by resoun ful trwe, clanly al the couenaunt that I the kynge asked, saf that thou schal siker me, segge, by thi trawthe, that thou schal seche me thi-self, where-so thou hopes I may be funde vpon folde, and foch the such wages as thou deles me to day, bifore this douthe ryche.” “Where schulde I wale the,” quod Gauan, “where is thy place? I wot neuer where thou wonyes, by hym that me wroght, ne I know not the, knyght, thy cort, ne thi name. But teche me truly therto, and telle me howe thou hattes, and I schal ware alle my wyt to wynne me theder, and that I swere the for sothe, and by my seker traweth.” “That is in-nogh in nwe yer, hit nedes no more,” quod the gome in the grene to Gawan the hende, “Yif I the telle trwly, quen I the tape haue, and thou me smothely hath smyten, smartly I the teche of my hous, and my home, and myn owen nome, then may thou frayst my fare, and forwardes holde, and if I spende no speche, thenne spedes thou the better, for thou may leng in thy londe, and layt no fyrre, but slokes; ta now thy grymme tole to the, and let se how thou cnokes.” “Gladly sir, for sothe,” quod Gawan; his ax he strokes.",
          e: "“By God,” said the Green Knight, “Sir Gawain, it pleases me well that I shall take from your fist what I have sought here; and you have readily rehearsed, in plain reason, every clause of the covenant I asked of the king — save only that you must pledge me, sir, on your troth, that you shall seek me yourself wherever you may suppose me to be found on the earth, and fetch yourself such wages as you deal me today, before this rich company.” “Where shall I look for you?” said Gawain. “Where is your place? I know not at all where you dwell, by Him that made me; nor do I know your court, knight, nor your name. But teach me truly the way, and tell me how you are called, and I shall lay out all my wit to win there — and that I swear in truth, by my sure pledge.” “That is enough at New Year, no more is needed,” said the man in the green to courteous Gawain. “If I tell you truly, when I have taken the blow and you have smoothly struck me, swiftly shall I teach you of my house and my home and my own name. Then you may seek my dwelling and keep the bargain. But if I do not give speech at all, the better for you — for you may stay in your land and look no further; but enough of this. Take now your grim tool to you, and let us see how you knock.” “Gladly, sir, in truth,” said Gawain; he stroked his axe." },

        { w: "The grene knyght vpon grounde graythely hym dresses, a littel lut with the hede, the lere he discoueres, his longe louelych lokkes he layd ouer his croun. Let the naked nec to the note schewe. Gauan gripped to his ax, and gederes hit on hyght, the kay fot on the folde he be-fore sette, let hit doun lyghtly lyght on the naked, that the scharp of the schalk schyndered the bones, and schrank thurgh the schyire grece, and scade hit in twynne, that the bit of the broun stel bot on the grounde. The fayre hede fro the halce hit felle to the erthe, that fele hit foyned wyth her fete, there hit forth roled; the blod brayd fro the body, that blykked on the grene; and nawther faltered ne fel the freke neuer the helder, but stythly he start forth vpon styf schonkes, and runyschly he raght out, there as renkkes stoden, laght to his lufly hed, and lyft hit vp sone; and sythen boghes to his blonk, the brydel he cachches, steppes in to stel bawe and strydes alofte, and his hede by the here in his honde haldes; and as sadly the segge hym in his sadel sette, as non vnhap had hym ayled, thaghe hedles he were, in stedde; he brayde his bluk aboute, that vgly bodi that bledde, moni on of hym had doute, by that his resounes were redde.",
          e: "The Green Knight upon the ground readied himself, bent his head a little and bared his face — laid his long lovely locks over his crown, and let the bare neck show for the work. Gawain gripped his axe and gathered it on high, set his left foot forward on the floor, and let it come down lightly upon the naked neck — so that the sharp blade shore through the bones, sank through the bright flesh and parted it in two, and the bit of the brown steel bit on the ground beneath. The fair head fell from the neck to the earth; many kicked it about with their feet as it rolled forth; the blood spurted from the body, glittering on the green. And yet the man neither faltered nor fell the slightest the more — but stoutly he started forth upon stiff legs, and savagely he reached out where the men stood by, caught hold of his handsome head and lifted it up at once; and then turned to his horse, caught the bridle, stepped into the stirrup and strode aloft — holding his head by the hair in his hand. And as soberly the man sat in his saddle as though no harm had come to him, though headless he was, in the place. He swung his trunk about — that ugly body that bled — and many a man feared him by the time his words were read out." },

        { w: "For the hede in his honde he haldes vp euen, to-ward the derrest on the dece he dresses the face, and hit lyfte vp the yghe-lyddes, and loked ful brode, and meled thus much with his muthe, as ye may now here. “Loke, Gawan, thou be graythe to go as thou hettes, and layte as lelly til thou me, lude, fynde, as thou hath hette in this halle, herande thise knyghtes; to the grene chapel thou chose, I charge the to fotte, such a dunt as thou hath dalt disserued thou habbes, to be yederly yolden on nw yeres morn; the knyght of the grene chapel men knowen me mony; for-thi me forto fynde if thou frayste3, fayles thou neuer, therfore com, other recreaunt be calde the be-houeus.” With a runisch rout the raynes he tornes, halled out at the hal-dor, his hed in his hande, that the fyr of the flynt flaghe fro fole houes. To quat kyth he be-com, knwe non there, neuermore then thay wyste fram quethen he was wonnen; what thenne? The kyng and Gawen thare, at that grene thay laghe and grenne, yet breued was hit ful bare, a meruayl among tho menne.",
          e: "For he held his head up straight in his hand, and toward the noblest on the dais he turned the face; and it lifted up its eyelids and stared full wide, and spoke this much with its mouth, as you may now hear. “See, Gawain, that you be ready to go as you have promised, and seek truly until you find me, sir, as you have promised in this hall in the hearing of these knights. To the Green Chapel you shall go, I charge you, to fetch such a blow as you have dealt me — well-deserved you have it — to be readily given back on New Year's morning. As Knight of the Green Chapel many know me; therefore, if you set out to find me, you shall not fail. Come therefore — or recreant must you be called.” With a fierce wrench he turned the reins, and bolted out at the hall door, his head in his hand, so that fire flew from the flint of his horse's hooves. To what country he had come, none there knew, no more than they knew from whence he had been gotten. What then? The king and Gawain there at that green one laughed and grinned — yet truly it was made known among those men as a marvel.",
          n: "The talking severed head is the moment everyone remembers. The Green Chapel — wherever it is — becomes the haunted destination of the whole poem." },

        { w: "Thaghe Arther the hende kyng at hert hade wonder, he let no semblaunt be sene, but sayde ful hyghe to the comlych quene, wyth cortays speche, “Dere dame, to day demay yow neuer; wel by-commes such craft vpon cristmasse, laykyng of enterludes, to laghe and to syng. Among thise, kynde caroles of knyghtes and ladyes; neuer-the-lece to my mete I may me wel dres, for I haf sen a selly, I may not for-sake.” He glent vpon sir Gawen, and gaynly he sayde, “Now sir, heng vp thyn ax, that hath in-nogh hewen.” And hit was don abof the dece, on doser to henge, ther alle men for meruayl myght on hit loke, and by trwe tytel ther-of to telle the wonder. Thenne thay boghed to a borde thise burnes to-geder, the kyng and the gode knyght, and kene men hem serued of alle dayntyghes double, as derrest myght falle, wyth alle maner of mete and mynstralcie bothe; wyth wele walt thay that day, til worthed an ende, in londe. Now thenk wel, sir Gawan, for wothe that thou ne wonde, this auenture forto frayn, that thou hath tan on honde.",
          e: "Though Arthur the courteous king had wonder in his heart, he let no sign of it be seen, but said full loudly to the comely queen, with courteous speech: “Dear lady, do not let this day dismay you ever; such craft well becomes Christmastide — the playing of interludes, the laughter and the singing among the gentle carols of knights and ladies. Nevertheless I may now address myself well to my meat, for I have seen a marvel, I cannot deny it.” He glanced at Sir Gawain and graciously said: “Now, sir, hang up your axe — it has hewn enough.” And it was placed above the dais, hung on the tapestry-screen, where all men might look upon it for the marvel and tell the wonder of it by the true title that hung there. Then they bowed to a board together, these men — the king and the good knight — and keen attendants served them with all dainties doubled, as the noblest might befall, with every kind of meat and minstrelsy both. With joy they made their way through that day until it came to its end, in the land. Now think well, Sir Gawain — for no danger shrink from going to find the adventure that you have taken in hand.",
          n: "Fitt I closes here on the narrator's address to Gawain. Fitt II opens with the long, slow turn of the seasons toward next Christmas, the great arming-scene, and the ride into the wilderness." },
      ],
    },
    {
      title: "Fitt II. The seasons, the arming, the road to the castle",
      segments: [
        { w: "This hanselle hath Arthur of auenturus on fyrst, in yonge yer, for he yerned yelpyng to here. Thaghe hym wordes were wane, when thay to sete wenten; now ar thay stoken of sturne werk staf-ful her hond. Gawan was glad to begynne those gomnes in halle, bot thaghe the ende be heuy, haf ye no wonder; for thaghe men ben mery in mynde, quen thay han mayn drynk, a yere yernes ful yerne, and yeldes neuer lyke, the forme to the fynisment foldes ful selden. For-thy this yol ouer-yede, and the yere after, and uche sesoun serlepes sued after other; after crysten-masse com the crabbed lentoun, that fraystes flesch wyth the fysche and fode more symple; bot thenne the weder of the worlde wyth wynter hit threpes, colde clenges adoun, cloudes uplyften, schyre schedes the rayn in schowres ful warme, falles vpon fayre flat, flowres there schewen, bothe groundes and the greues grene ar her wedes, bryddes busken to bylde and bremlych syngen, for solace of the softe somer that sues ther after, by bonk; and blossumes bolne to blowe, by rawes rych and ronk; then notes noble innoghe ar herde in wod so wlonk.",
          e: "Such a New Year's handsel Arthur has had of adventures at first, in the young year, for he had yearned to hear such bold tales. Though words had failed him when they went to their seats, now their hands are stocked staff-full with stern work. Gawain was glad to begin those games in the hall — but though the ending be heavy, do not marvel at it; for though men are merry in mind when they have mighty drink, a year hurries on full eagerly, and never two are alike — the beginning to the finishing seldom folds together. So this Yule passed by, and the year after, and each season severally followed the other. After Christmas came the crabbed Lent that tries the flesh with fish and food more simple; but then the weather of the world struggles with winter — cold cringes down, the clouds lift up, the rain sheds clear in showers full warm, falls upon fair flats, and flowers show there; both grounds and groves are green-clad again; birds busy themselves to build and bravely sing for joy of the soft summer that follows after, by the hillside; and blossoms swell to blow, by rows rich and rank; and then noble notes enough are heard in the woods so lovely." },

        { w: "After the sesoun of somer wyth the soft wyndes, quen Zeferus syfles hym-self on sedes and erbes, wela-wynne is the wort that woxes ther-oute, when the donkande dewe dropes of the leues, to bide a blysful blusch of the bryght sunne. Bot then hyghes heruest, and hardenes hym sone, warnes hym for the wynter to wax ful rype; he dryues wyth droght the dust for to ryse, fro the face of the folde to flyghe ful hyghe; wrothe wynde of the welkyn wrasteles with the sunne, the leues lancen fro the lynde, and lyghten on the grounde, and al grayes the gres, that grene was ere; thenne al rypes and rotes that ros vpon fyrst, and thus yirnes the yere in yisterdayes mony, and wynter wyndes ayayn, as the worlde askes no sage. Til megel-mas mone was cumen wyth wynter wage; then thenkkes Gawan ful sone of his anious uyage.",
          e: "After the season of summer with the soft winds, when Zephyrus whispers himself on seeds and herbs, full-glad is the green that grows out of doors, when the dewy drops fall from the leaves to bide the blissful glance of the bright sun. But then harvest hastens, and hardens itself soon, warning the world to ripen for the winter; with drought it drives the dust to rise from the face of the field to fly full high. A wrathful wind of the welkin wrestles with the sun; the leaves loose from the linden and alight on the ground, and all greys the grass that was green before; then all ripens and rots that rose at first, and thus the year yields itself in many yesterdays, and winter winds round again, as the world asks, with no question. Till the Michaelmas moon was come with winter's wage — then Gawain full soon thinks of his anxious voyage." },

        { w: "Yet quyl al-hal-day with Arther he lenges, and he made a fare on that fest, for the frekes sake, with much reuel and ryche of the rounde table; knyghtes ful cortays and comlych ladies, al for luf of that lede in longynge thay were, bot neuer-the-lece ne the later thay neuened bot merthe, mony joyles for that ientyle japes ther maden. For aftter mete, with mournyng he meles to his eme, and spekes of his passage, and pertly he sayde, “Now, lege lorde of my lyf, leue I yow ask; ye knowe the cost of this cace, kepe I no more to telle yow tenes ther-of neuer bot trifel; bot I am boun to the bur barely to morne, to sech the gome of the grene, as god wyl me wysse.” Thenne the best of the burgh boghed to-geder, Aywan, and Errik, and other ful mony, Sir Doddinaual de Sauage, the duk of Clarence, Launcelot, and Lyonel, and Lucan the gode, sir Boos, and sir Byduer, big men bothe, and mony other menskful, with Mador de la Port. Alle this compayny of court com the kyng nerre, for to counseyl the knyght, with care at her hert; there was much derue doel driuen in the sale, that so worthe as Wawan schulde wende on that ernde, to dryghe a delful dynt, and dele no more wyth bronde. The knyght mad ay god chere, and sayde, “quat schuld I wonde, of destines derf and dere, what may mon do bot fonde?”",
          e: "Yet till All Hallows' Day with Arthur he lingers, and the king made a feast on that day for his nephew's sake, with much rich revel of the Round Table; knights full courteous and comely ladies, all in longing for love of that man they were, but nevertheless and no later they spoke only of mirth — many a sad one for that gentle one made jests there. For after meat, mourning, he speaks to his uncle, and openly says of his passage: “Now, liege lord of my life, leave I ask of you; you know the case of this matter, I will no longer trouble you with its sorrows beyond a trifle; but I am bound for the blow tomorrow without fail, to seek the man of the green, as God shall guide me.” Then the best of the burgh gathered together: Ywain and Eric and many more, Sir Doddinaval the Savage, the Duke of Clarence, Launcelot and Lionel and Lucan the Good, Sir Bors and Sir Bedivere, big men both, and many other honourable men, with Mador de la Port. All this company of court came nearer the king, to counsel the knight, with care in their hearts; there was much sharp sorrow driven in the hall, that one so worthy as Gawain should go on that errand, to endure a dolorous blow, and deal no more with sword. The knight ever made good cheer, and said, “What should I shrink from? Of destinies dire and dear, what may a man do but try?”" },

        { w: "He dowelles ther al that day, and dresses on the morn, askes erly hys armes, and alle were thay broght. Fyrst a tule tapit, tyght ouer the flet, and miche was the gyld gere that glent ther alofte; the stif mon steppes ther-on, and the stel hondoles, dubbed in a dublet of a dere tars, and sythen a crafty capados, closed aloft, that wyth a bryght blaunner was bounden with-inne. Thenne set thay the sabatouns vpon the segge fotes, his leges lapped in stel with luflych greues, with polaynes piched ther-to, policed ful clene, aboute his knes knaged wyth knotes of golde; queme quyssewes then, that coyntlych closed his thik thrawen thyghes with thwonges to-tachched; and sythen the brawden bryne of bryght stel rynges vmbe-weued that wyghe vpon wlonk stuffe; and wel bornyst brace vpon his bothe armes, with gode cowters and gay, and gloues of plate, and alle the godlych gere that hym gayn schulde, that tyde; wyth ryche cote armure, his gold spores spend with pryde, gurde wyth a bront ful sure, with silk sayn vmbe his syde.",
          e: "He dwells there all that day and dresses on the morn, asks early for his arms, and all were brought. First a tiled tapet was tightened over the floor, and much was the gilt gear that glittered aloft; the stiff man steps thereon and handles the steel — dubbed in a doublet of dear Tarsic silk, and then a crafty hood-cape closed above, that was bordered within with bright ermine. Then they set the sabatons upon the man's feet, his legs lapped in steel with lovely greaves, with kneecaps pitched thereto, polished full clean, knotted about his knees with knots of gold; then comely cuisses that cunningly enclosed his thick-thrawn thighs, attached with thongs. And then the braided byrnie of bright steel rings webbed that man about, upon a stuff most stately; and well-burnished braces upon both his arms, with good elbow-pieces gay, and gloves of plate, and all the goodly gear that should serve him that time. With rich coat-armour, his gold spurs spent with pride, girded with a sure sword, with a silk sash about his side." },

        { w: "When he was hasped in armes, his harnays was ryche, the lest lachet outher loupe lemed of golde; so harnayst as he was, he herknes his masse, offred and honoured at the heghe auter. Sythen he comes to the kyng and to his cort feres, laches lufly his leue at lordes and ladyes; and thay hym kyst and conueyed, bikende hym to Kryst. By that was Gryngolet grayth, and gurde with a sadel, that glemed ful gayly with mony golde frenges, ay quere naylet ful nwe for that note ryched; the brydel barred aboute, with bryght golde bounden; the apparayl of the payttrure, and of the proude skyrtes, the cropore, and the couertor, acorded wyth the arsounes; and al was rayled on red ryche golde nayles, that al glytered and glent as glem of the sunne. Thenne hentes he the holme, and hastily hit kysses, that was stapled stifly, and stoffed wyth-inne; hit was hyghe on his hede, hasped bihynde, wyth a lyghtli urysoun ouer the auentayle, enbrawden and bounden wyth the best gemmes, on brode sylkyn borde, and bryddes on semes, as papiayes paynted pernyng bitwene, tortors and trulofes entayled so thyk, as mony burde ther aboute had ben seuen wynter in toune; the cercle was more o prys, that vmbe-clypped hys croun, of diamauntes a deuys, that bothe were bryght and broun.",
          e: "When he was clasped in armour, his harness was rich, the least latch or loop gleamed of gold. So harnessed as he was, he hearkens his Mass, offered and honoured at the high altar. Then he comes to the king and to his court fellows, lovingly takes his leave of lords and ladies; and they kissed him and conveyed him, commending him to Christ. By then Gringolet was groomed and girded with a saddle that gleamed full gaily with many golden fringes, everywhere new-nailed and richly prepared for that errand. The bridle was barred about, bound with bright gold. The appointments of the breast-band and of the proud trappings, the crupper and the covering, all matched the saddle-bows; and all was railed with red rich-gold nails, that all glittered and glanced as a gleam of the sun. Then he takes up the helm and hastily kisses it — stapled stiffly, stuffed within; high it sat on his head, clasped behind, with a light circlet over the aventail, embroidered and set with the best of gems on broad silken borders, with birds upon the seams — parrots painted preening between, turtle-doves and true-love knots cut so thick as if many a maiden had worked seven winters at it in town. The circle that clasped his crown was more precious yet, of diamonds devised, that were both bright and brown." },

        { w: "Then thay schewed hym the schelde, that was of schyr goules, wyth the pentangel de-paynt of pure golde hwes; he braydes hit by the baude-ryk, aboute the hals kestes, that bisemed the segge semlyly fayre. And quy the pentangel apendes to that prynce noble, I am in tent yow to telle, thof tary hyt me schulde. Hit is a syngne that Salamon set sum-quyle, in bytoknyng of trawthe, by tytle that hit habbes, for hit is a figure that haldes fyue poyntes, and uche lyne vmbe-lappes and loukes in other, and ay quere hit is endeles, and Englych hit callen ouer-al, as I here, the endeles knot. For-thy hit acordes to this knyght, and to his cler armes, for ay faythful in fyue and sere fyue sythes, Gawan was for gode knawen, and as golde pured, voyded of uche vylany, wyth vertues ennourned in mote; for-thy the pen-tangel nwe he ber in schelde and cote, as tulk of tale most trwe, and gentylest knyght of lote.",
          e: "Then they showed him the shield, that was of bright gules, with the pentangle painted on it in pure gold hues; he hangs it by the baldric and casts it about his neck, where it became the man seemly and fair. And why the pentangle belongs to that noble prince I am of a mind to tell you, though it tarry me. It is a sign that Solomon set in time past, in token of truth, by the title it bears — for it is a figure that holds five points, and each line overlaps and locks into another, and everywhere it is endless; and in English they call it overall, as I hear, the endless knot. Therefore it accords to this knight and to his clear arms, for ever faithful in five and many times five, Gawain was known for good, and as gold tested-pure, void of every villainy, with virtues adorned in his fortress. So the new pentangle he bore on shield and coat, as the man of speech most true, and the gentlest knight in bearing.",
          n: "The pentangle digression: the poem's moral architecture. The endless five-times-five is Gawain's bond, and the rest of the poem is the testing of it." },

        { w: "Fyrst he was funden fautles in his fyue wyttes, and efte fayled neuer the freke in his fyue fyngres, and alle his afyaunce vpon folde was in the fyue woundes that Cryst kaght on the croys, as the crede telles; and quere-so-euer thys mon in melly was stad, his thro thoght was in that, thurghe alle other thynges, that alle his forsnes he fong at the fyue joyes that the hende heuen quene had of hir chylde. At this cause the knyght comlyche hade in the more half of his schelde hir ymage depaynted, that quen he blusched ther-to, his belde neuer payred. The fyfth fyue that I finde that the frek vsed was fraunchyse, and felaghschyp for-be al thyng; his clannes and his cortaysye croked were neuer, and pite, that passes alle poyntes, thyse pure fyue were harder happed on that hathel then on any other. Now alle these fyue sythes, for-sothe, were fetled on this knyght, and uchone halched in other, that non ende hade, and fyched vpon fyue poyntes, that fayld neuer, ne samned neuer in no syde, ne sundred nouther, with-outen ende at any noke I-quere fynde, where-euer the gomen bygan, or glod to an ende. Ther-fore on his schene schelde schapen was the knot, thus alle wyth red golde vpon rede gowles, that is the pure pentaungel wyth the peple called, with lore. Now grayhed is Gawan gay, and laght his launce ryght thore, and gef hem alle goud day, he wende for euer more.",
          e: "First he was found faultless in his five wits, and second the knight never failed in his five fingers, and all his faith on earth was in the five wounds that Christ caught on the cross, as the creed tells; and wheresoever this man stood in battle, his eager thought was in this, above all other things: that all his strength he took from the five joys that the gentle queen of heaven had of her child. For this cause the knight had comely depicted in the inner half of his shield her image, so that whenever he glanced thereto his courage never failed. The fifth five I find that the man used were generosity and fellowship above all things, his cleanness and his courtesy never crooked, and pity, that passes all points — these pure five were harder hasped on this lord than on any other. Now all these five fives, in truth, were fettled on this knight, and each one halched into another, that had no end, and fixed upon five points that failed never, nor came together on any side, nor were sundered either, without end at any nook anywhere to find, wheresoever the figure began or glided to an end. Therefore on his shining shield was shaped the knot, thus all in red gold upon red gules — that is what the people call, with learning, the pure pentangle. Now is gay Gawain ready, and seized his lance right there, and bade them all good day; he went for evermore." },

        { w: "He sperred the sted with the spures, and sprong on his way, so stif that the ston fyr stroke out ther-after. Al that segh that semly syked in hert, and sayde sothly al same segges til other, carande for that comly, “by Kryst, hit is scathe that thou, leude, schal be lost, that art of lyf noble! To fynde hys fere vpon folde, in fayth is not ethe; warloker to haf wroght had more wyt bene, and haf dyght yonder dere a duk to haue worthed; a lowande leder of ledes in londe hym wel semes, and so had better haf ben then britned to noght, hadet wyth an aluisch mon, for angardes pryde. Who knew euer any kyng such counsel to take, as knyghtes in caueulouns on cryst-masse gomnes!” Wel much was the warme water that waltered of yghen, when that semly syre soght fro tho wones that daye; he made non abode, bot wyghtly went hys way; mony wylsum way he rode, the bok as I herde say.",
          e: "He spurred the steed with his spurs and sprang on his way, so stiffly that the stone-fire struck out behind. All that saw that seemly one sighed in heart, and said softly each man to another, mourning for that comely one: “By Christ, it is a sad pity that you, sir, shall be lost — you that are of life so noble! To find his peer on earth, in truth, is not easy. It would have been more sensible work, and far more sense, to have set yonder dear man up as a duke — a glowing leader of men in the land he well seems; and far better had that been than to be cut to nothing, beheaded by an elvish man for arrogance and pride. Who has ever known a king take such counsel as knights take in their wrangles at Christmas games?” Many was the warm water that welled from eyes when that seemly sire set forth from those dwellings that day. He made no halt, but went on his way swiftly. Many a winding way he rode — the book, as I have heard, says so.",
          n: "The court's grief is also the poem's first sceptical voice: the New Year game was \"angardes pryde\" — arrogant pride — and it has cost them their best knight." },

        { w: "Now rides this renk thurghe the ryalme of Logres, sir Gauan on Godes halue, thaghe hym no gomen thoght. Oft, leudles alone, he lenges on nyghtes, ther he fonde noght hym byfore the fare that he lyked; hade he no fere bot his fole, by frythes and dounes, ne no gome bot God, by gate wyth to karp, til that he neghed ful noghe in-to the Northe Wales. Alle the iles of Anglesay on lyft half he haldes, and fares ouer the fordes by the for-londes, ouer at the Holy-Hede, til he hade eft bonk in the wyldrenesse of Wyrale; wonde ther bot lyte that auther God other gome wyth goud hert louied. And ay he frayned, as he ferde, at frekes that he met, if thay hade herde any karp of a knyght grene, in any grounde ther-aboute, of the grene chapel; and al nykked hym wyth nay, that neuer in her lyue thay seghe neuer no segge that was of suche hwes of grene. The knyght tok gates straunge, in mony a bonk vnbene; his cher ful oft con chaunge, that chapel er he myght sene.",
          e: "Now rides this man through the realm of Logres, Sir Gawain on God's behalf, though it seemed to him no game. Often, alone without companion, he lay at night where he found not the fare before him that he liked. He had no comrade but his foal, through forests and downs, and no man but God to speak with by the way, till he came full nigh into North Wales. All the isles of Anglesey he keeps on his left, and fares over the fords by the forelands, over at Holyhead, till he reached the bank again in the wilderness of Wirral — where dwelt but few that loved either God or man with a good heart. And ever he asked, as he fared, of folk that he met, if they had heard any talk of a knight green, in any ground thereabout, of the Green Chapel — and all denied him with “nay,” that never in their lives had they seen any man that was of such a hue of green. The knight took roads unknown, by many a bank unblythe; his cheer full oft did change, before that chapel he might see." },

        { w: "Mony klyf he ouer-clambe in contrayes straunge, fer floten fro his frendes fremedly he rydes; at uche warthe other water ther the wyghe passed, he fonde a foo hym byfore, bot ferly hit were, and that so foule and so felle, that feght hym by-hode. So mony meruayl by mount ther the mon fyndes, hit were to tore for to telle of the tenthe dole. Sumwhyle wyth wormes he werres, and with wolues als, sumwhyle wyth wodwos, that woned in the knarres, bothe wyth bulles and beres, and bores other-quyle, and etaynes, that hym anelede, of the heghe felle. Nade he ben dughty and dryghe, and dryghtyn had serued, douteles he hade ben ded, and dreped ful ofte. For werre wrathed hym not so much, that wynter was wors, when the colde cler water fro the cloudes schadden, and fres er hit falle myght to the fale erthe; ner slayn wyth the slete he sleped in his yrnes, mo nyghtes then innoghe in naked rokkes, ther as claterande fro the crest the colde borne rennes, and henged heghe ouer his hede in hard ÿsse-ikkles. Thus in peryl, and payne, and plytes ful harde, by contray caryes this knyght, tyl kryst-masse euen, al one; the knyght wel that tyde, to Mary made his mone, that ho hym red to ryde, and wysse hym to sum wone.",
          e: "Many a cliff he climbed over in countries strange; far floated from his friends, friendlessly he rides. At every ford or water where the man passed, he found a foe before him, but a wonder it were, and that so foul and so fell that fight him behoved. So many a marvel by mount the man finds, it would be too hard to tell of the tenth part. Sometimes with serpents he wars, and with wolves too; sometimes with wood-men that dwelt in the crags; with bulls and bears, and boars by other turns, and giants that hounded him from the high fells. Had he not been doughty and stout, and served the Lord, doubtless he had been dead and slain full often. For warfare wrathed him not so much: the winter was worse, when the cold clear water from the clouds shed and froze ere it might fall to the pale earth. Nearly slain with the sleet, he slept in his irons more nights than enough on naked rocks, where chattering from the crest the cold burn runs and hung high over his head in hard icicles. Thus in peril and pain and plights full hard the knight carries himself by country, till Christmas Eve, all alone. The knight well at that time to Mary made his moan, that she would teach him where to ride, and guide him to some dwelling." },

        { w: "By a mounte on the morne meryly he rydes, into a forest ful dep, that ferly was wylde, hyghe hilles on uche a halue, and holt wodes vnder, of hore okes ful hoge a hundreth to-geder; the hasel and the haghe-thorne were harled al samen, with roghe raged mosse rayled ay-where, with mony bryddes vnblythe vpon bare twyges, that pitosly ther piped for pyne of the colde. The gome vpon Gryngolet glydes hem vnder, thurghe mony misy and myre, mon al hym one, carande for his costes, lest he ne keuer schulde, to se the seruyce of that syre, that on that self nyght of a burde was borne, oure baret to quelle. And therfore sykyng he sayde, “I beseche the, lorde, and Mary, that is myldest moder so dere, of sum herber, ther heghly I myght here masse, ande thy matynes to-morne, mekely I ask, and ther-to prestly I pray my pater and aue, and crede.” He rode in his prayere, and cryed for his mysdede; he sayned hym in sythes sere, and sayde “cros Kryst me spede!”",
          e: "By a mountain on the morn merrily he rides, into a forest full deep, that wondrously was wild — high hills on each side and dense woods under, of hoary oaks full huge a hundred together; the hazel and the hawthorn were tangled all together, with rough ragged moss arrayed everywhere, with many sad birds upon bare twigs that piteously there piped for pain of the cold. The man on Gringolet glides beneath them, through many a bog and mire, a man all alone, caring for his case, lest he should not contrive to see the service of that Sire, who on that self night of a maid was born, our trouble to quell. And therefore sighing he said: “I beseech you, Lord, and Mary, who are the mildest mother so dear — of some lodging, that I might highly hear Mass and your matins tomorrow morn, meekly I ask; and to it promptly I pray my Pater and Ave, and Creed.” He rode in his prayer and cried for his misdeed; he signed himself many times, and said, “Cross of Christ, speed me!”" },

        { w: "Nade he sayned hym-self, segge, bot thrye, er he was war in the wod of a won in a mote, abof a launde, on a lawe, loken vnder boghes, of mony borelych bole, aboute by the diches; a castel the comlokest that euer knyght aghte, pyched on a prayere, a park al aboute, with a pyked palays, pyned ful thik, that vmbe-teghe mony tre mo then two myle. That holde on that on syde the hathel auysed, as hit schemered and schon thurghe the schyre okes; thenne hath he hendly of his helme, and heghly he thonkes Jesus and saynt Gilyan, that gentyle ar bothe, that cortaysly hade hym kydde, and his cry herkened. “Now bone hostel,” cothe the burne, “I beseche yow yette!” Thenne gederes he to Gryngolet with the gilt heles, and he ful chauncely hath chosen to the chef gate, that broght bremly the burne to the bryge ende, in haste; the bryge was breme vp-brayde, the yates wer stoken faste, the walles were wel arayed, hit dut no wyndes blaste.",
          e: "He had not signed himself, the knight, but thrice ere he was aware in the wood of a dwelling in a moat. Above a lawn, on a knoll, locked under boughs of many a sturdy trunk, surrounded by ditches — a castle, the comeliest that ever knight owned, pitched on a meadow with a park all about, with a peaked palisade pinned full thick that encompassed many a tree, more than two miles. That hold the man eyed from one side, as it shimmered and shone through the bright oaks. Then he gently takes off his helm and highly he thanks Jesus and Saint Julian — both of them gentle — who had courteously shown him favour and hearkened his cry. “Now good lodging,” said the man, “I beseech you yet!” Then he urged Gringolet on with the gilt heels, and well by chance he had chosen the chief road, that briskly brought the knight to the bridge end, in haste. The bridge was sharply drawn up, the gates were shut fast, the walls were well arrayed; it dreaded no blast of wind." },

        { w: "The burne bode on bonk, that on blonk houed, of the depe double dich that drof to the place, the walle wod in the water wonderly depe, ande eft a ful huge heghte hit haled vpon lofte, of harde hewen ston vp to the tables, enbaned vnder the abataylment, in the best lawe; and sythen garytes ful gaye gered bi-twene, wyth mony luflych loupe, that louked ful clene; a better barbican that burne blusched vpon neuer. And innermore he be-helde that halle ful hyghe, towre telded bytwene trochet ful thik, fayre fylyoles that fyghed, and ferlyly long, with coruon coprounes, craftyly sleghe; chalk whyt chymnees ther ches he in-noghe, vpon bastel roues, that blenked ful quyte; so mony pynakle payntet was poudred ay quere, among the castel carneles, clambred so thik, that pared out of papure purely hit semed. The fre freke on the fole hit fayr innoghe thoght, if he myght keuer to com the cloyster wyth-inne, to herber in that hostel, whyl halyday lested, auinant; he calde, and sone ther com a porter pure plesaunt, on the wal his ernd he nome, and haylsed the knyght erraunt.",
          e: "The knight bode on the bank — he on his horse hovered — of the deep double ditch that drew round the place; the wall stood in the water wondrously deep, and afterwards rose to a full huge height aloft, of hard-hewn stone up to the tables, embanked under the battlements in the best fashion. And then watchtowers full gaily geared between, with many a lovely loophole that locked full clean — a better barbican that knight had never gazed upon. And further within he beheld that hall full high, towers built between with thick-set pinnacles, fair finials fitted and wondrously long, with carved capitals craftily cunning. Chalk-white chimneys there he could choose many, upon stronghold roofs that blinked full white. So many a painted pinnacle was sown everywhere among the castle crenellations, clambered so thick, that it purely seemed pared out of paper. The free knight on the foal thought it fair enough, if he might contrive to come within the cloister, to find harbour in that hostel while the holiday lasted, becoming. He called, and soon there came a porter pure-pleasant, on the wall took his errand, and hailed the knight errant." },

        { w: "“Gode sir,” quod Gawan, “woldes thou go myn ernde, to the heghe lorde of this hous, herber to craue?” “Ye, by Peter,” quod the porter, “and purely I trowe, that ye be, wyghe, welcum to won quyle yow lykes.” Then yede that wyghe ayayn awythe, and folke frely hym wyth, to fonge the knyght. Thay let doun the grete draght, and derely out yeden, and kneled doun on her knes vpon the colde erthe, to welcum this ilk wyghe, as worthy hom thoght. Thay yolden hym the brode yate, yarked vp wyde, and he hem raysed rekenly, and rod ouer the brygge; sere segges hym sesed by sadel, quel he lyght, and sythen stabeled his stede stif men innoghe. Knyghtes and swyeres comen doun thenne, for to bryng this burne wyth blys in-to halle; quen he hef vp his helme, ther hyghed innoghe for to hent hit at his honde, the hende to seruen; his bronde and his blasoun bothe thay token. Then haylsed he ful hendly tho hatheles vch one, and mony proud mon ther presed, that prynce to honour; alle hasped in his heghe wede to halle thay hym wonnen, ther fayre fyre vpon flet fersly brenned. Thenne the lorde of the lede loutes fro his chambre, for to mete wyth menske the mon on the flor; he sayde, “ye ar welcum to welde as yow lykes, that here is, al is yowre awen, to haue at yowre wylle and welde.” “Graunt mercy,” quod Gawayn, “ther Kryst hit yow forylde,” as frekes that semed fayn, ayther other in armes con felde.",
          e: "“Good sir,” said Gawain, “would you take my errand to the high lord of this house, to crave a lodging?” “Yes, by Peter,” said the porter, “and purely I believe that you, sir, are welcome to stay as long as it pleases you.” Then went that man away briskly, and folk freely with him, to receive the knight. They let down the great drawbridge and went dearly out, and kneeled down on their knees upon the cold earth, to welcome this same man, as worthy him they thought. They yielded him the broad gate, opened up wide, and he raised them graciously, and rode over the bridge; several men seized him by the saddle while he alighted, and then stabled his steed many stiff men. Knights and squires came down then, to bring this man with bliss into the hall; when he heaved up his helm, there hastened enough to take it from his hand, the courteous one to serve; his sword and his blazon both they took. Then he hailed full courteously each of those lords, and many a proud man pressed there, that prince to honour; all clasped in his high gear, to hall they won him, where a fair fire on the floor fiercely burned. Then the lord of the people steps out from his chamber to meet with honour the man on the floor; he said, “You are welcome to wield as you like; what is here, all is your own, to have at your will and command.” “Grant mercy,” said Gawain, “may Christ requite it you,” as men that seemed glad, each folded other in arms." },

        { w: "Gawayn glyght on the gome that godly hym gret, and thught hit a bolde burne that the burgh aghte, a hoge hathel for the nones, and of hyghe elde; brode bryght was his berde, and al beuer hwed, sturne stif on the strythe on stal-worth schonkes, felle face as the fyre, and fre of hys speche; and wel hym semed for sothe, as the segge thught, to lede a lortschyp in lee of leudes ful gode. The lorde hym charred to a chambre, and chefly cumaundes to delyuer hym a leude, hym loghly to serue; and there were boun at his bode burnes innoghe, that broght hym to a bryght boure, ther beddyng was noble, of cortynes of clene sylk, wyth cler golde hemmes, and couertores ful curious, with comlych panes, of bryght blaunnier aboue enbrawded bisydes, rudeles rennande on ropes, red golde rynges, tapytes tyght to the woghe, of tuly and tars, and vnder fete, on the flet, of folghande sute. Ther he was dispoyled, wyth speches of myerthe, the burn of his bruny, and of his bryght wedes; ryche robes ful rad renkkes hem broghten, for to charge, and to chaunge, and chose of the best. Sone as he on hent, and happed ther-inne, that sete on hym semly, wyth saylande skyrtes, the ver by his uisage verayly hit semed wel negh to vche hathel alle on hwes, lowande and lufly, alle his lymmes vnder, that a comloker knyght neuer Kryst made, hem thoght. Whethen in worlde he were, hit semed as he myght be prynce with-outen pere, in felde ther felle men fyght.",
          e: "Gawain glanced at the man that goodly greeted him, and thought him a bold lord that owned the burgh — a huge man for the nonce, and of high age; broad and bright was his beard, and all beaver-hued, stern and stiff in his stride on stalwart shanks, a face fell as the fire, and free of his speech; and well it seemed him in truth, as the knight thought, to lead a lordship in the lee of leaders full good. The lord turned him to a chamber, and chiefly commanded that a page be given him, lowly to serve him; and there were ready at his bidding men enough, who brought him to a bright bower where the bedding was noble — of curtains of clean silk, with clear gold hems, and coverings full curious with comely panels, of bright ermine above embroidered besides; runners running on ropes, red-gold rings; tapestries tight to the wall, of Toulouse and Tarsia, and underfoot on the floor, of matching suit. There he was disrobed, with speeches of mirth, the knight of his byrnie and of his bright weeds; rich robes full readily men brought him, to put on, to change, and choose of the best. As soon as he took one and clad himself therein, that sat on him seemly with sailing skirts, the spring by his face verily it seemed to nigh every man, in all its hues, glowing and lovely, with all his limbs under, that a comelier knight Christ never made, so they thought. Wherever in the world he was, it seemed he might be a prince without peer, in field where fierce men fight." },

        { w: "A cheyer by-fore the chemné, ther charcole brenned, was graythed for sir Gawan, graythely with clothes, whyssynes vpon queldepoyntes, that koynt wer bothe; and thenne a mere mantyle was on that mon cast, of a broun bleeaunt, enbrauded ful ryche, and fayre furred wyth-inne with felles of the best, alle of ermyn in erde, his hode of the same; and he sete in that settel semlych ryche, and achaufed hym chefly, and thenne his cher mended. Sone was telded vp a tapit, on trestes ful fayre, clad wyth a clene clothe, that cler quyt schewed, sanap, and salure, and syluer-in spones; the wyghe wesche at his wylle, and went to his mete. Segges hym serued semly innoghe, wyth sere sewes and sete, sesounde of the best, double felde, as hit falles, and fele kyn fisches; summe baken in bred, summe brad on the gledes, summe sothen, summe in sewe, sauered with spyces, and ay sawes so sleghes, that the segge lyked. The freke calde hit a fest ful frely and ofte, ful hendely, quen alle the hatheles re-hayted hym at ones, as hende; “This penaunce now ye take, and eft hit schal amende.” That mon much merthe con make, for wyn in his hed that wende.",
          e: "A chair before the chimney, where charcoal burned, was made ready for Sir Gawain, neatly with cloths, cushions on quilted pads, that both were comely; and then a fine mantle was cast upon that man, of a brown bleeaunt embroidered full rich and fair-furred within with the fells of the best — all of ermine on earth, his hood of the same; and he sat in that settle seemly rich, and warmed himself well, and then his cheer mended. Soon a table was set up on trestles full fair, clad with a clean cloth that showed clear white, napkins and salt-cellars and silver spoons; the man washed at his will, and went to his meat. Men served him seemly enough, with several stews and stocks, seasoned of the best, doubled-served, as it falls, and many kinds of fishes — some baked in bread, some broiled on the embers, some sodden, some in stew, savoured with spices, and ever such sly sauces that the man liked. The fellow called it a feast full freely and often, full graciously, when all the lords rehighted him at once as fine: “This penance now you take, and after it shall amend.” That man much mirth could make, for wine in his head that went." },

        { w: "Thenne was spyed and spured vpon spare wyse, by preue poyntes of that prynce put to hym-seluen, that he be-knew cortaysly of the court that he were, that athel Arthure the hende haldes hym one, that is the ryche ryal kyng of the rounde table; and hit was Wawen hym-self that in that won sytte3, comen to that krystmasse, as case hym then lymped. When the lorde hade lerned that he the leude hade, loude laghed he ther-at, so lef hit hym thoght, and alle the men in that mote maden much joye, to apere in his presense prestly that tyme, that alle prys, and prowes, and pured thewes apendes to hys persoun, and praysed is euer, by-fore alle men vpon molde, his mensk is the most. Uch segge ful softly sayde to his fere, “Now schal we semlych se sleghtes of thewes, and the teccheles termes of talkyng noble, wich spede is in speche, vnspurd may we lerne, syn we haf fonged that fyne fader of nurture; God hath geuen vus his grace godly for sothe, that such a gest as Gawan grantes vus to haue, when burnes blythe of his burthe schal sitte and synge. In menyng of maneres mere, this burne now schal vus bryng; I hope that may hym here, schal lerne of luf-talkyng.”",
          e: "Then he was spied upon and asked, in a sparing way, by private questions put to him by that prince, that he confessed courteously he was of the court — that noble Arthur the courteous alone keeps him, who is the rich royal king of the Round Table; and it was Gawain himself who sat in that dwelling, come to that Christmas as chance then chimed for him. When the lord had learned what guest he had, loudly he laughed thereat, so dear it him thought, and all the men in that moat made much joy to appear in his presence promptly at that time — for all prize and prowess and pure manners belong to his person, and ever is he praised before all men upon earth, his honour is the most. Each man full softly said to his fellow: “Now shall we seemly see slights of manners, and the unstained terms of talking noble; what skill is in speech, unasked we may learn, since we have caught that fine father of nurture. God has given us his grace, godly for sooth, that such a guest as Gawain he grants us to have, when men shall sit and sing blithe of His birth. In the meaning of pure manners this man now shall bring us; I hope that he that may him hear shall learn of love-talking.”",
          n: "An exquisitely sly setup. The court ridicules Gawain's reputation as the master of courtly love-talk — the very reputation the Lady will test him on for three days running in Fitt III." },

        { w: "By that the diner was done, and the dere vp, hit was negh at the nyght neghed the tyme; chaplaynes to the chapeles chosen the gate, rungen ful rychely, ryght as thay schulden, to the hersum euensong of the hyghe tyde. The lorde loutes ther-to, and the lady als, in-to a comly closet coyntly ho entres; Gawan glydes ful gay, and gos theder sone; the lorde laches hym by the lappe, and ledes hym to sytte, and couthly hym knowes, and calles hym his nome, and sayde he was the welcomest wyghe of the worlde; and he hym thonkked throly, and ayther halched other, and seten soberly samen the seruise-quyle. Thenne lyst the lady to loke on the knyght. Thenne com ho of hir closet, with mony cler burdes, ho was the fayrest in felle, of flesche and of lyre, and of compas, and colour, and costes of alle other, and wener then Wenore, as the wyghe thoght. He ches thurghe the chaunsel, to cheryche that hende; an other lady hir lad by the lyft honde, that was alder then ho, an auncian hit semed, and heghly honowred with hatheles aboute. Bot vn-lyke on to loke tho ladyes were, for if the yonge was yep, yolghe was that other; riche red on that on rayled ay quere, rugh ronkled cheke3 that other on rolled; kerchofes of that on wyth mony cler perles, hir brest and hir bryght throte bare displayed, schon schyrer then snawe, that scheder on hilles; that other wyth a gorger was gered ouer the swyre, chymbled ouer hir blake chyn with mylk-quyte vayles, hir frount folden in sylk, enfoubled ay quere, toret and treieted with tryfles aboute, that noght was bare of that burde bot the blake broghes, the tweyne yghen, and the nase, the naked lyppes, and those were soure to se, and sellyly blered; a mensk lady on molde mon may hir calle, for gode; hir body was schort and thik, hir buttokes bay and brode, more lykker-wys on to lyk, was that scho hade on lode.",
          e: "By the time dinner was done and the company up, it was near the time when night neared; chaplains to the chapels chose the way, rang full richly right as they should, to the gracious evensong of the high tide. The lord turns thither, and the lady also: into a comely closet quaintly she enters. Gawain glides full gay and goes there soon; the lord catches him by the lap and leads him to sit, and kindly knows him and calls him by his name, and said he was the most welcome man of the world; and he thanked him heartily, and each embraced the other, and they sat soberly together for the service-while. Then the lady desired to look on the knight. Then she came from her closet with many fair maidens — she was the fairest in skin, of flesh and of face, and of bearing and colour and customs above all others, and weener than Guinevere, as the man thought. He passed through the chancel to cherish that gentle one; another lady led her by the left hand, who was older than she — an ancient she seemed, and highly honoured by the lords about. But unlike to look on the two ladies were: for if the young was sprightly, sallow was that other; rich red on the one was rayled everywhere, rough wrinkled cheeks on the other rolled; kerchiefs on the one with many clear pearls, her breast and her bright throat were bare displayed, shining whiter than the snow that sheds on hills; the other with a gorget was geared over the neck, wrapped over her black chin with milk-white veils, her brow folded in silk, enwrapped everywhere, treaded and torreted with trifles about — that nothing of that woman was bare but the black brows, the two eyes, and the nose, the naked lips, and those were sour to see, and singularly bleared. A worshipful lady on earth a man may call her, for good. Her body was short and thick; her buttocks bay and broad — far the more delicious to look on was the one she had in tow.",
          n: "The poem's first introduction of the two ladies — the dazzling young one and the strangely-veiled old one. The old hag is no servant: she is the agent the whole tale turns on. Pearl Poet plants her here, says nothing more, and lets the revelation wait for Fitt IV." },

        { w: "When Gawayn glyght on that gay, that graciously loked, wyth leue laght of the lorde he went hem ayaynes; the alder he haylses, heldande ful lowe, the loueloker he lappes a lyttel in armes, he kysses hir comlyly, and knyghtly he meles; thay kallen hym of a quoyntaunce, and he hit quyk askes to be her seruaunt sothly, if hem-self lyked. Thay tan hym bytwene hem, wyth talkyng hym leden to chambre, to chemné, and chefly thay asken spyces, that vn-sparely men speded hom to bryng, and the wynne-lych wyne ther-with vche tyme. The lorde luflych aloft lepes ful ofte, mynned merthe to be made vpon mony sythes, hent heghly of his hode, and on a spere henged, and wayned hom to wynne the worchip ther-of, that most myrthe myght mene that crystenmas whyle; “and I schal fonde, by my fayth, to fylter wyth the best, er me wont the wedes, with help of my frendes.” Thus wyth laghande lotes the lorde hit tayt makes, for to glade sir Gawayn with gomnes in halle that nyght; til that hit was tyme, the kyng comaundet lyght; sir Gawen his leue con nyme, and to his bed hym dyght.",
          e: "When Gawain glanced at that gay one that graciously looked, with leave caught from the lord he went toward them; the elder he hails, bending full low; the lovelier he laps a little in arms — he kisses her comely and knightly he speaks. They call him of acquaintance, and he quick asks to be her servant truly, if themselves liked it. They take him between them, with talking they lead him to chamber, to chimney, and chiefly they ask for spices, which men unsparingly sped them to bring, and the joyous wine with them every time. The lord lovely aloft leapt full often, minded mirth to be made many times over — caught his hood from his head and hung it on a spear, and waved them to win the honour of it: he that could make most mirth that Christmas while. “And I shall try, by my faith, to filter with the best, ere the garment is wanting to me, with the help of my friends.” Thus with laughing words the lord makes it lively, to gladden Sir Gawain with games in hall that night; till that it was time, the king commanded a light; Sir Gawain his leave he took, and to his bed himself dight." },

        { w: "On the morne, as vch mon mynes that tyme, that dryghtyn for oure destyné to deghe was borne, wele waxes in vche a won in worlde, for his sake; so did hit there on that day, thurghe dayntes mony, bothe at mes and at mele, messes ful quaynt derf men vpon dece drest of the best. The olde auncian wyf heghest ho syttes; the lorde lufly her by lent, as I trowe; Gawan and the gay burde to-geder thay seten, euen in-myddes, as the messe metely come; and sythen thurghe al the sale, as hem best semed, by vche grome at his degre graythely was serued. Ther was mete, ther was myrthe, ther was much joye, that for to telle ther-of me tene were, and to poynte hit yet I pyned me parauenture; bot yet I wot that Wawen and the wale burde such comfort of her compaynye caghten to-geder, thurghe her dere dalyaunce of her derne wordes, wyth clene cortays carp, closed fro fylthe; and hor play was passande vche prynce gomen, in vayres; trumpes and nakerys, much pypyng ther repayres, vche mon tented hys, and thay two tented thayres.",
          e: "On the morn, as each man minds that time when the Lord for our destiny was born to die, weal waxes in every dwelling in the world, for his sake; so it did there on that day, through dainties many. Both at servings and at meal, full quaint courses stern men upon the dais dressed of the best. The old ancient wife sits highest; the lord lovingly lent beside her, as I believe; Gawain and the gay maiden together they sat, even in the middle, as the courses duly came; and then through all the hall, as best suited them, every man at his degree was readily served. There was meat, there was mirth, there was much joy, that to tell thereof me trouble were, and to point it out yet I pined me peradventure; but yet I know that Gawain and the choice maiden such comfort of their company caught together, through their dear dalliance of secret words, with clean courteous talk, closed from filth — and their play was passing every prince's game, in truth. Trumpets and nakers, much piping there repairs; each man tended his, and the two tended theirs." },

        { w: "Much dut was ther dryuen that day and that other, and the thryd as thro thronge in ther-after; the joye of sayn Jones day was gentyle to here, and was the last of the layk, leudes ther thoghten. Ther wer gestes to go vpon the gray morne, for-thy wonderly thay woke, and the wyn dronken, daunsed ful dreghly wyth dere caroles; at the last, when hit was late, thay lachen her leue, vchon to wende on his way, that was wyghe stronge. Gawan gef hym god-day, the god mon hym lachches, ledes hym to his awen chambre, the chymné bysyde, and there he draghes hym on-dryghe, and derely hym thonkkes, of the wynne worschip that he hym wayned hade, as to honour his hous on that hyghe tyde, and enbelyse his burgh with his bele chere. “I-wysse sir, quyl I leue, me worthes the better, that Gawayn hath ben my gest, at Goddes awen fest.” “Grant merci sir,” quod Gawayn, “in god fayth hit is yowres, al the honour is your awen, the heghe kyng yow yelde; and I am wyghe at your wylle, to worch youre hest, as I am halden ther-to, in hyghe and in loghe, by ryght.” The lorde fast can hym payne, to holde lenger the knyght; to hym answres Gawayn, by non way that he myght.",
          e: "Much delight was there driven that day and the next, and the third as eagerly thronged in thereafter; the joy of Saint John's Day was gentle to hear, and was the last of the play, the people there thought. There were guests to go on the grey morn, and so they wondrously sat up, and drank the wine, danced dreamily with dear carols; at the last, when it was late, they took their leave, each one to wend on his way, that was a wight strong. Gawain bids him good day; the good man catches him, leads him to his own chamber, beside the chimney; and there he draws him aside and dearly thanks him for the winning worship that he had granted him, in honouring his house on that high tide and embellishing his burgh with his bright cheer. “Indeed, sir, while I live I am the better, that Gawain has been my guest at God's own feast.” “Grant mercy, sir,” said Gawain, “in good faith it is yours; all the honour is your own — the high King yield it you; and I am a man at your will, to work your behest, as I am held thereto, in high and in low, by right.” The lord fast strives himself, to hold the knight longer; to him Gawain answers, in no way that he might." },

        { w: "Then frayned the freke ful fayre at him-seluen, quat derne dede had hym dryuen, at that dere tyme, so kenly fro the kynges kourt to kayre al his one, er the halidayes holly were halet out of toun? “For sothe sir,” quod the segge, “ye sayn bot the trawthe — a heghe ernde and a hasty me hade fro tho wones, for I am sumned my selfe to sech to a place — I wot not in worlde whederwarde to wende, hit to fynde; I nolde, bot if I hit negh myght on nw yeres morne, for alle the londe in-wyth Logres, so me oure lorde help! For-thy, sir, this enquest I require yow here, that ye me telle with trawthe, if euer ye tale herde of the grene chapel, quere hit on grounde stondes, and of the knyght that hit kepes, of colour of grene? Ther was stabled by statut a steuen vus by-twene, to mete that mon at that mere, yif I myght last; and of that ilk nw yere bot neked now wontes, and I wolde loke on that lede, if God me let wolde, gladloker, by Goddes sun, then any god welde! For-thy, I-wysse, by yowre wylle, wende me by-houes, naf I now to busy bot bare thre dayes, and me als fayn to falle feye as fayly of myyn ernde.” Thenne laghande quod the lorde, “now leng the by-houes, for I schal teche yow to that terme by the tymes ende, the grene chapayle vpon grounde, greue yow no more; bot ye schal be in yowre bed, burne, at thyn ese, quyle forth dayes, and ferk on the fyrst of the yere, and cum to that merk at mydmorn, to make quat yow lykes, in spenne; dowelles whyle new yeres daye, and rys, and raykes thenne, mon schal yow sette in waye, hit is not two myle henne.”",
          e: "Then the lord asked him full fair what darling deed had driven him, at that dear time, so keenly from the king's court to ride all alone, ere the holidays were wholly drawn out of town. “For sooth, sir,” said the knight, “you say but the truth — a high errand and a hasty took me from those dwellings; for I am summoned myself to seek to a place — I know not in the world whither to wend, to find it; I would not, unless I might near it by New Year's morn, for all the land within Logres, so help me our Lord. Therefore, sir, this enquest I require of you here — that you tell me with truth, if ever you heard tale of the Green Chapel, where it on ground stands, and of the knight that keeps it, of colour of green. There was set by statute an appointment us between, to meet that man at that mark, if I might last; and of that very New Year but little now wants, and I would look on that man, if God would let me, gladder, by God's son, than any goods I might hold. Therefore indeed, by your leave, depart me behoves; I have now to busy but bare three days, and as soon would I fall dead as fail of my errand.” Then laughing said the lord: “Now you must linger, for I shall teach you to that term by the time's end — the Green Chapel on the ground, grieve you no more. You shall be in your bed, knight, at your ease while forth into the days, and fare on the first of the year, and come to that mark at mid-morning, to make what you like in that place. Dwell while New Year's Day, and rise, and rake then; a man shall set you in the way — it is not two miles hence.”",
          n: "The Pearl Poet's quietest, deadliest hinge. The lord casually reveals the Green Chapel is two miles away — meaning Gawain has arrived where he was always being driven. The whole castle, the whole hospitality, the whole exchange-game that follows, is the trap." },

        { w: "Thenne was Gawan ful glad, and gomenly he laghed,— “Now I thonk yow thryuandely thurghe alle other thynge, now acheued is my chaunce, I schal at your wylle dowelle, and elles do quat ye demen.” Thenne sesed hym the syre, and set hym bysyde, let the ladies be fette, to lyke hem the better; ther was seme solace by hem-self stille; the lorde let for luf lotes so myry, as wyghe that wolde of his wyte, ne wyst quat he myght. Thenne he carped to the knyght, criande loude, “ye han demed to do the dede that I bidde; wyl ye halde this hes here at thys ones?” “Ye sir, for-sothe,” sayd the segge trwe, “whyl I byde in yowre borghe, be bayn to yowre hest.” “For ye haf trauayled,” quod the tulk, “towen fro ferre, and sythen waked me wyth, ye arn not wel waryst, nauther of sostnaunce ne of slepe, sothly I knowe; ye schal lenge in your lofte, and lyghe in your ese, to morn quyle the messe-quyle, and to mete wende, when ye wyl, wyth my wyf, that wyth yow schal sitte, and comfort yow with compayny, til I to cort torne; ye lende; and I schal erly ryse, on huntyng wyl I wende.” Gauayn grantes alle thyse, hym heldande, as the hende.",
          e: "Then was Gawain full glad, and gamely he laughed: “Now I thank you thrivingly above all other things — now achieved is my chance; I shall at your will dwell, and else do what you deem.” Then the sire seized him, and set him beside, let the ladies be fetched to like them the better; there was seemly solace by themselves still. The lord let, for love, his words be so merry, as a man that would be out of his wit and knew not what he might. Then he spoke to the knight, crying loud: “You have agreed to do the deed I bid — will you hold this behest here at this once?” “Yes sir, for sooth,” said the knight true, “while I bide in your burgh, obedient to your behest.” “For you have travelled,” said the lord, “come from far, and afterwards waked with me — you are not well restored, neither of sustenance nor of sleep, sothly I know; you shall lenge in your loft, and lie at your ease, till tomorrow's mass-while, and to meat wend when you will, with my wife, who with you shall sit, and comfort you with company, till I to court return; you stay. And I shall early rise; on hunting I will wend.” Gawain grants all these, bending to him, as the courteous one." },

        { w: "“Yet firre,” quod the freke, “a forwarde we make: quat-so-euer I wynne in the wod, hit worthes to youres, and quat chek so ye acheue, chaunge me ther-forne; swete, swap we so, sware with trawthe, quether, leude, so lymp lere other better.” “By God,” quod Gawayn the gode, “I grant ther-tylle, and that yow lyst forto layke, lef hit me thynkes.” “Who bringes vus this beuerage, this bargayn is maked,” so sayde the lorde of that lede; thay laghed vchone, thay dronken, and daylyeden, and dalten vntyghtel, thise lordes and ladyes, quyle that hem lyked; and sythen with frenkysch fare and fele fayre lotes thay stoden, and stemed, and stylly speken, kysten ful comlyly, and kaghten her leue. With mony leude ful lyght, and lemande torches, vche burne to his bed was broght at the laste, ful softe; to bed yet er thay yede, recorded couenauntes ofte; the olde lorde of that leude couthe wel halde layk a-lofte.",
          e: "“Yet further,” said the man, “a covenant we make: whatsoever I win in the wood, it shall fall to yours; and whatever check you achieve, change me therefor; sweet, swap we so, swear with truth, whether, sir, the lot fall worse or better.” “By God,” said Gawain the good, “I grant thereto; and that you list to play, dear it seems to me.” “Who brings us this beverage, this bargain is made,” so said the lord of that people; they laughed each one. They drank, and dallied, and dealt without restraint, these lords and ladies, while it pleased them; and then with French fashion and many fair gestures they stood, and lingered, and spoke softly, kissed full comely, and caught their leave. With many a man full light, and gleaming torches, each man to his bed was brought at the last, full soft. To bed yet ere they went, they recorded the covenants oft. The old lord of that people knew well how to hold play aloft.",
          n: "The exchange-of-winnings bargain. Bertilak is genial, casual, almost playful — but the trade he proposes is the one that the rest of the poem turns on. Fitt III, the heart of the poem, is the playing-out of this bargain across three days." },
      ],
    },
  ],
};
